  <note>
    <title>__ mm, measured from consecutive serial sections from B1-B11 spanning 55 mm in thickness</title>
    <created>20200929T055733Z</created>
    <updated>20240126T020221Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>__ mm, measured from consecutive serial sections from B1-B11 spanning 55 mm  in thickness (pT3).</div><div><br/></div><div>measured from</div><div>  serial sequential sampling of tumor from sections B1 to</div><div>  B11 spanning 55 mm in thickness (pT3). </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Abscess</title>
    <created>20170306T083923Z</created>
    <updated>20181109T100600Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows mammary tissue cores exhibiting a heavy infiltrate of acute and chronic</div><div>inflammatory cells, and scattered histiocytes and multinucleated giant cells. The GMS and PAS stains are negative for fungal organism.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, no invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Adenosis and stromal fibrosis</title>
    <created>20170227T025532Z</created>
    <updated>20170227T025554Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows florid proliferation of mammary glands with preserved myoepithelial cells that are demonstrated by p63 and SMMHC immunostainings. The stroma surrounding</div><div>the proliferative glands is fibrotic and shows spindled fibroblasts. Focal aggregate of foamy histiocytes along with lymphocytic infiltrate is also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>No evidence of malignancy is observed in these materials. Clinico-radiological correlations are recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADH [ADF] [F]</title>
    <created>20190712T065950Z</created>
    <updated>20250515T045301Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Atypical ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>There is focal population of monotonous cells arranged in solid and cribriform patterns (_ mm in maximum dimension), suggestive of atypical ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microcalcifications are present inside the ADH and in benign mammary acini.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the proliferative ductal epithelial cells show focal loss of CK5/6. P63 highlights the surrounding myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ALH</title>
    <created>20170512T030003Z</created>
    <updated>20251013T023449Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div><a href="evernote:///view/26224745/s227/7423c386-33b9-4b82-9eb5-f19fa124cc3f#0de4e3fb-e415-4641-b6df-80dab25eebaf/9fa88e94-9907-434d-8e18-634482c75c16/">Atypical lobular hyperplasia.</a></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show expended acini featuring proliferation of discohesive cells with intracytoplasmic vacuoles, involving less than half of the acini of a lobular unit.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Atypical lobular hyperplasia.</div><div>There is solid, discohesive proliferation of cells that are monomorphic, small, with pale pink cytoplasm, uniform oval nuclei, and indistinct nucleoli, but it does not distend the acini</div><div>An immunohistochemical stain for E-cadherin is negative in the atypical focus, supporting the diagnosis of ALH.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>benign cysts with inflammation.</title>
    <created>20190610T023533Z</created>
    <updated>20201223T090651Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>benign cysts with inflammation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show cystic spaces lined by double layer of flat or cuboidal cells with focal rupture and inflammatory response with macrophages deposition.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Benign mammary tissue, core biopsy</title>
    <created>20160310T015318Z</created>
    <updated>20250213T022706Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>  各位主任、醫師：</div><div><br/></div><div>今天乳癌團隊會議討論決議，core biopsy 結果僅是normal mammary tissue時，病理報告能加註警示，以免臨床醫師誤以為是benign lesion，而錯失進一步處理。</div><div><br/></div><div>雖然於2015年1月已有發通知給大家，但科內仍有不一致的做法，在此重發通知，並統一電腦系統中的格式。若報告用手寫的同仁，也請用一樣的診斷字句(Normal mammary tissue)，及加註警語 (Note: The specimen may be not representative for the lesion. Re-biopsy is recommended.)。</div><div>謝謝！</div><div><br/></div><div>1.病人通常是在有懷疑病變的情況下做core biopsy，例如palpable mass 或影像下看到病變。所以當我們在core biopsy的切片看到”良性組織”，應該分出是”normal mammary tissue” 或”benign lesion (e.g. Sclerosing adenosis, DH…)”。</div><div>2.如果是”normal mammary tissue”，core biopsy很可能沒扎到可疑的病變。臨床或影像懷疑時應做進一步處理。若我們在這樣的情況下，診斷打”benign mammary tissue”，臨床醫師容易會誤以為是benign lesion，而錯失進一步處理。</div><div>3.請統一使用電腦報告格式代碼BRE33 (Normal mammary tissue)</div><div><br/></div><div><b>Diagnosis:</b>
Normal mammary tissue, right/left breast (<i>,</i>), core biopsy.</div><div><b>Note:</b> The specimen may not be representative of the lesion. Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><b>Microscopic Description:</b>
The core biopsy samples contain normal breast ducts and lobules, along with fibrous and adipose stroma. No pathological changes, including microcalcifications or signs of malignancy, are present in the specimens. Based on imaging findings, the specimen may not be representative of the lesion. Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>李文瑛醫師</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Benign mammary tissue.</title>
    <created>20161110T145630Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014816Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Benign mammary tissue.</div><div><br/></div><div><b>Microscopic description:</b></div><div>The section reveals benign mammary acini and ductules within a fibrotic stroma, accompanied by focal cystic dilatation. Myoepithelial cells are highlighted by p63 immunostain. No microcalcifications or signs of malignancy are present.</div><div>Re-biopsy is advised if there is strong clinical suspicion of malignancy.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Benign phyllodes tumor</title>
    <created>20160810T103156Z</created>
    <updated>20250127T030609Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Benign phyllodes tumor</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show a well-circumscribed tumor revealing leafy architecture with epithelium-lined clefts. The stromal elements are mildly cellular with low mitotic activity (&lt;5 per 10 HPF). No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Benign phyllodes tumor</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show a lobulated tumor composed of clefts lined by benign ductal epithelia and myxoid cellular stroma. The stromal cells do not exhibit pleomorphism and mitoses are rare. Benign phyllodes tumor is considered. The section margin is free of tumor but very closed. Follow-up for local recurrence is recommended.</div><div>    </div><div>Benign phyllodes tumor</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show a well-circumscribed tumor revealing leafy architecture with epithelium-lined clefts. The stromal elements are mildly cellular with peri-epithelial accentuation. The stromal nuclei are monomorphic with low mitotic activity (1 per 10 HPF). No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CK5/6</title>
    <created>20170414T154419Z</created>
    <updated>20170414T154425Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Staining for basal-like cells (CK5/6) is absent across the lesion, with satisfactory internal controls in small uninvolved ducts and overlying skin.     <br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20211126T045101Z</created>
    <updated>20241001T044226Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Complex fibroadenoma.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Sections shows a fibroadenoma associated with sclerosing adenosis, epithelial calcifications, and papillary apocrine metaplasia.</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">NOTE: Complex fibroadenomas are associated with a minimal increase in relative cancer risk.</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="--en-markholder:true;"><br/></span></span></div><div><a href="evernote:///view/26224745/s227/b74b6139-bf9a-48d6-b650-e1ed503e72e7/b79d4e17-abc0-4a31-a8af-507fce45085f">Fibroepithelial lesion</a></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20211026T020747Z</created>
    <updated>20211026T020828Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>complex sclerosing lesion with usual ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show irregularly shaped epithelial cell nests in a</div><div>fibroelastotic stroma. Focal usual ductal hyperplasia is</div><div>seen. P63 stain demonstrates the presence of myoepithelial</div><div>cells around the celllular nests.</div><div>No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20191002T084618Z</created>
    <updated>20201111T023439Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Consistent with accessory breast.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>It shows scattered mammary ductules in a fibroadipose stroma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Cystic neutrophilic granulomatous mastitis with abscess formation. See Note.</title>
    <created>20200402T023332Z</created>
    <updated>20251029T045831Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Cystic neutrophilic granulomatous mastitis with abscess formation. See Note.</div><div>Granulomatous inflammation witn CNGM-pattern. See Note.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show non-caseating granuloma, accompanied by formation of round to oval cystic spaces rimmed by neutrophils (microabscesses).</div><div>No microorganisms are identified on special stains (PAS, AFS). Lactational change is seen in the surrounding mammary parenchyma. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: The CNGM (cystic neutrophilic granulomatous mastitis)-pattern is possible associated with gram positive bacilli such as Corynebacterium species.</div><div><br/></div><div><a href="https://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/breastcysticgranulomatousmastitis.html">Pathology outline</a></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DCIS biopsy</title>
    <created>20241212T081452Z</created>
    <updated>20251008T084900Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Ductal carcinoma in situ.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic type: Ductal carcinoma in situ.</div><div>Nuclear grade: Grade I (low) Grade II (intermediate) Grade III (high) </div><div>Architectural pattern: Comedo Cribriform  Micropapillary Papillary Solid </div><div>Necrosis: Not identified</div><div>Present, focal (small foci or single cell necrosis)</div><div>Present, central (expansive "comedo" necrosis) </div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %*, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %*, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DCIS comedo, biopsy</title>
    <created>20160812T014247Z</created>
    <updated>20220208T092016Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Ductal carcinoma in situ, comedo-type.</span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><br/></span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Section shows breast tissue revealing nests of ductular proliferation with focal comedo-type necrosis. The proliferative epithelial cells show enlarged nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli.</span> </span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;">Immunohistochemically, SMMHC and p63 highlight the myoepithelial cells around the in-situ lesions, confirming the diagnosis.</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">1. ER (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %*, weak / moderate / strong)</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">2. PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %*, weak / moderate / strong)</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><br/></span></div><hr/><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 12px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Ductal carcinoma in situ, comedo-type.</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><br/></span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Histologic type: </span><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Ductal carcinoma in situ</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Nuclear grade: Grade III (high)</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Architectural pattern: Comedo Cribriform  Micropapillary Papillary Solid</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Necrosis: </span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Present, focal (small foci or single cell necrosis)</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Present, central (ex</span><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">pansive comedo necrosis)</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Immunohistochemical study:</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">SMMHC highlights the surrounding myoepithelial cells</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Estrogen receptor: Positive Negative (%, weak / moderate / strong)</span></div><div style="text-align: start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial;">Progesterone receptor: Positive Negative (%,weak / moderate / strong)</span></div></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DCIS, solid, cribriform</title>
    <created>20160812T014503Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T090508Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Ductal carcinoma in situ.</span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span style="--en-markholder:true;"><br/></span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 13px;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Microscopic description: </span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 13px;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Section shows breast tissue revealing ductular proliferation with solid and cribriform patterns. The proliferative epithelial cells show enlarged and rounded nuclei with increased mitotic activity. </span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><br/></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 13px;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Immunohistochemically, the epithelial cells in the ductal carcinoma in situ show no CK5/6 expression. P63 and SMMHC highlight the surrounding myoepithelial cells, confirming the diagnosis.</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><br/></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Histologic type: Ductal carcinoma in situ</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Nuclear grade: Grade I (low) Grade II (intermediate) Grade III (high)</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Architectural pattern: Comedo Cribriform  Micropapillary Papillary Solid</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Necrosis: Not identified</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Present, focal (small foci or single cell necrosis)</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Present, central (expansive “comedo” necrosis)</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Immunohistochemical study:</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">SMMHC highlights the surrounding myoepithelial cells</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Estrogen receptor: Positive Negative (%, weak / moderate / strong)</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Progesterone receptor: Positive Negative (%,weak / moderate / strong)</span></span></span></div><div style="text-align:start;"><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DCIS_檢體不夠評估大小</title>
    <created>20161110T145540Z</created>
    <updated>20161110T145554Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Sections A and B show mainly non-comedo type ducatal carcinoma in situ with one and two small foci (all mearsuring around 1 mm in diameter) of invasive lesion, respectively. One of the small invasive lesion in Section B is at the surgical margin with cauterization artifact, making the determination of tumor size impossible. In addition, there might be residual tumor left behind. The pathologic tumor stage is at least at T1a. Final tumor staging will be determined by total excisional specimen.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20200708T044532Z</created>
    <updated>20200708T044553Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>desmoid fibromatosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show spindle cells in long sweeping fascicles or</div><div>loose storiform pattern infiltrating mammary lobuldes, duct</div><div>and adipose tissue. These cells are uniform with small</div><div>nuclei and absence of nuclear pleomorphism or mitotic</div><div>figures. Infiltrate of lymphoplasmacytic cells is focally</div><div>seen. Small to medium-sized stromal blood vessels with</div><div>perivascular edema is discerned. Usual ductal hyperplasia is</div><div>also noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for SMA</div><div>but not p63, AE1/AE3, ALK or 34betaE12. Weakly</div><div>staining for CD34 is focally seen. Nucelar beta-catenin</div><div>expression is noted.</div><div>Taken together, this is a desmoid fibromatosis.</div><div>The surgical margin is involved.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: Desmoid fibromatosis is locally aggressive but non-</div><div>metastasizing neoplasm with propensity for local recurrence.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190123T012439Z</created>
    <updated>20260608T083931Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>file:///C:\Users\h3d0\Desktop\Form_Huang\1.1-breast%20DCIS%20checklist.doc</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Ductal carcinoma in situ associated with microinvasive carcinoma (pT1mi)</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>1. Histologic type: ductal carcinoma in situ with microinvasive carcinoma</div><div>2. Histologic grade (Nottingham modification of the Bloom-</div><div>   Richardson grading system): grade __</div><div>   Tubule formation: </div><div>   Nuclear pleomorphism: </div><div>   Mitotic count: </div><div>   NOTE: microinvasion is not graded according to Cancer</div><div>   Protocol Templates of College of American Pathologists.</div><div>3. Maximum size of invasive cancer: &lt;1 mm, measured on the histologic slide</div><div>   [pT1mi:&lt;=1 mm (microinvasion)]</div><div>4. Extent of tumor:</div><div>   Skin: </div><div>   Chest wall invasion deeper than pectoralis muscle: Absent</div><div>   Nipple: </div><div>5. Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS):</div><div>   Tumor size (mm):  mm</div><div>   Nuclear grade: Grade III (high)</div><div>   Architectural pattern: </div><div>   Necrosis: </div><div>Not identified</div><div>Present, focal (small foci or single cell necrosis)</div><div>Present, central (expansive “comedo” necrosis)</div><div>6. Extensive intraductal carcinoma status: Positive</div><div>7. Peritumoral lymphovascular invasion: Absent</div><div>8. Perineural invasion: Absent</div><ol start="9"><li><div><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color:#010101;">Microcalcification: Absent / Present (inside the DCIS and non-tumor mammary acini)</span></span></span></div></li></ol><div>10. Surgical margin:</div><div>   Basal: free,  cm in distance</div><div>   Nearest peripheral: free,  cm in distance</div><div>11. Lymph nodes (Positive/Total): </div><div>12. Treatment Effect: not applicable</div><div>13. Immunohistochemical study: (performed on section A7)</div><div>    P63 and SMMHC: Absence of myoepithelial rimming</div><div>Estrogen receptor: Positive Negative (%, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>Progesterone receptor: Positive Negative (%,weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>    HER-2/neu protein: Negative (_+)</div><div>    Ki-67:  nuclear staining</div><div>14. pTNM: pT1miN__ (AJCC cancer staging system, 8th edition)</div><div>15. TNM descriptors: not applicable.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>FEA, flat epithelial atypia</title>
    <created>20170729T095319Z</created>
    <updated>20250515T045124Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Flat epithelial atypia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a picture of flat epithelial atypic, which is characterized by variably dilated acini lined by several layers of columnar epithelial cells with monomorphic nuclei. </div><div><br/></div><div>Radiological-clinical correlation is recommended for determining further management.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroadenoma [FA2] pericanalicular</title>
    <created>20200615T142530Z</created>
    <updated>20230612T031826Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Fibroadenoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show breast tissue with a well-defined nodule composed of</div><div>admixture of stromal and epithelial proliferation, which features stromal growth around patent ducst. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroadenoma [FA]</title>
    <created>20161021T101421Z</created>
    <updated>20241204T075013Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Fibroadenoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show breast tissue with a well-defined nodule composed of admixture of stromal and epithelial proliferation, which features compressed glandular spaces in a fibrohyalinized stroma.        </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroadenomatous changes (fibroadenomatoid hyperplasia)</title>
    <created>20200921T051853Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014859Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Fibroadenomatous changes (fibroadenomatoid hyperplasia)</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description: </div><div>Section shows changes similar to those seen in fibroadenomas but lacks the sharp circumscription. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibrocystic change with microcalcifications [FCC]</title>
    <created>20161110T145602Z</created>
    <updated>20230612T023815Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>Fibrocystic change with microcalcifications</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show round to ovoid cystically dilated spaces lined by epithelial and myoepithelial cells in a sclerotic stroma. Microcalcifications are present in the lumens. Adenosis is also seen. No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div>            </div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>usual ductal hyperplasia</div><div>There is focal proliferation of epithelial cells being positive for CK5/6 with heterogeneous staining pattern, consistent with usual ductal hyperplasia.</div><div>No malignancy is o<span>    </span>bserved.</div></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroepithelial lesion</title>
    <created>20161122T014120Z</created>
    <updated>20230526T022825Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Fibroepithelial lesion</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show myxofibrous stroma admixed with compressed glandular structures with focal usual ductal hyperplasia. Immunohistochemically, the myoepithelial cells are highlighted by SMMHC. Staining for CK5/6 is heterogeneously positive in the proliferative epithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroepithelial lesion [no IHC]</title>
    <created>20171130T023240Z</created>
    <updated>20240619T070127Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Fibroepithelial lesion.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows fibrous stroma with low cellularity, admixed with compressed glandular structures.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>The above-mentioned features can be consistent with a fibroadenoma or a benign phyllodes tumor.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20230419T084530Z</created>
    <updated>20230525T064535Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>fibroepithelial lesion, suspicious for phyllodes tumor. see NOTE.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows proliferation of ductal epithelial cells in focal papillary pattern in a fibromyxoid stroma. The stroma shows focally increased cellularity with mild to moderate nuclear atypia and increased mitotic figures.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the ductal epithelial cells are heterogeneously positive for ER and CK5/6. P63 and SMMHC highlight the myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: The overall features are highly suspicious for phyllodes tumor. The categories cannot be established in this biopsy specimen, as the tumor is not fully sampled.</div><div>Wide excision of the tumor is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>FISH report 範本</title>
    <created>20201026T013537Z</created>
    <updated>20201026T013622Z</updated>
