  <note>
    <title>Granulomatous mastitis</title>
    <created>20181003T052352Z</created>
    <updated>20240110T032619Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Granulomatous mastitis</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections shows mammary tissue exhibiting a heavy infiltrate</div><div>of inflammatory cells within fibroadipose tissue and around</div><div>mammary lobules. The infiltrate is composed of acute and</div><div>chronic inflammatory cells, histiocytes, accompanied by</div><div>granulation tissue formation. Focal granuloma formation</div><div>composed of epithelioid histiocytes and multinucleated giant</div><div>cells are also seen. A subset of the granulomas show cystic</div><div>space or microabscess formation.</div><div><br/></div><div>The PAS stain is negative for fungal organisms. No</div><div>mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast</div><div>stain. No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by CK(AE1/AE3).</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IDC, biopsy (D.D lobular)</title>
    <created>20160810T103235Z</created>
    <updated>20210817T022714Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows breast tissue infiltrated by neoplastic cells arranged in nests and focal Indian filing patterns. The tumor cells show plemorphic nuclei with occasional nucleoli.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express E-cadherin and P120 (membranous pattern), consistent with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY: </div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive /Low Positive (1-10% of cells with nuclear positivity)/ Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR(Ab): positive /Negative ( %).</div><div>3. HER-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0</div><div>4. Ki-67</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IDC, biopsy (glandular differentiation)</title>
    <created>20160829T082035Z</created>
    <updated>20201207T025351Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; widows: 2;"><div style="letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).<br/></div><div style="letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><br/></div><div style="letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">Microscopic description:</div><div style="letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">Section shows breast tissue cores infiltrated by nests of neoplastic cells with tubuloglandular differentiation and focal cribriform architecture. The tumor cells show slightly enlarged nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli.</div><div><br/></div><div>Histologic type: Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).</div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>  Grade I (score 3-5) / Grade II (score 6,7) / Grade III (score 8,9)</div><div>- Tubule formation: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>Majority of tumor greater than 75% (score = 1)</div><div>Moderate 10% to 75% (score = 2)</div><div>Minimal less than 10% (score = 3)   </div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>Small regular nuclei (score = 1)</div><div>Moderate increase in size, etc (score = 2)</div><div>Marked variation in size, nucleoli, chromatin clumping, etc (score = 3)</div><div>- Mitotic count: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>0- 3 mitoses per mm2 (score = 1)</div><div>4-7 mitoses per mm2 (score = 2)</div><div>>= 8 mitoses per mm2 (score = 3)</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive /Low Positive (1-10% of cells with nuclear positivity)/ Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div><div>4. Ki-67</div><div>5. P63 immunostaining demonstrates the absence of myoepithelial cells at the periphery of invasive focus.</div><div style="letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><div><br/></div><div>Note: This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.</div></div></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IDC, biopsy (有一點點gland)</title>
    <created>20160810T103254Z</created>
    <updated>20231017T084735Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows breast tissue strips infiltrated by neoplastic cells arranged in nests, cords, isolated cells and focal glandular patterns. The tumor cells show slightly enlarged nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli. </div><div><br/></div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>  Grade I (score 3-5) / Grade II (score 6,7) / Grade III (score 8,9)</div><div>- Tubule formation: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>- Mitotic count: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>0- 3 mitoses per mm2 (score = 1)</div><div>4-7 mitoses per mm2 (score = 2)</div><div>>= 8 mitoses per mm2 (score = 3)</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive /Low Positive (1-10% of cells with nuclear positivity)/ Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %*, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div><div>4. Ki-67</div><div>5. P63 immunostaining demonstrates the absence of myoepithelial cells at the peripheray of invasive focus.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IDC, biopsy NEW</title>
    <created>20170721T021812Z</created>
    <updated>20260408T021651Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>file:///C:\Users\h3d0\Desktop\S0810178%20temp.doc</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div style="--en-codeblock:true; --en-lineWrapping:false;box-sizing: border-box; padding: 8px; font-family: Monaco, Menlo, Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;, monospace; font-size: 12px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); border-top-left-radius: 4px; border-top-right-radius: 4px; border-bottom-right-radius: 4px; border-bottom-left-radius: 4px; background-color: rgb(251, 250, 248); border: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.14902); background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><div>Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic type: Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).</div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>  Grade I (score 3-5) / Grade II (score 6,7) / Grade III (score 8,9)</div><div>- Tubule formation: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>- Mitotic count: score 1/ 2/ 3</div><div>		</div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive (_%, weak / moderate / strong) / Low Positive (1-10% of cells with nuclear positivity) / Negative </div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive(_%, weak / moderate / strong) /Negative </div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div><div>4. Ki-67: _%</div><div>5. P63 immunostaining demonstrates the absence of myoepithelial cells at the periphery of invasive focus.</div><div>6. E-cadherin: Positive in membranous staining.</div><div>		</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><h2 style="--en-nodeId:94e9c545-c78b-4d69-985b-b1cbcec26869;">HER2 Result Criteria </h2><div>Negative (Score 0) No staining observed or Membrane stating that is incomplete and is faint/barely perceptible and within ≤10% of tumor cells </div><div><br/></div><div>Negative (Score 1+) Incomplete membrane staining that is faint/barely perceptible and within >10% of tumor cells* </div><div><br/></div><div>Equivocal (Score 2+)† Weak to moderate complete membrane staining in >10% of tumor cells or Circumferential membrane staining that is intense but within ≤10% of tumor cells* </div><div><br/></div><div>Positive (Score 3+) Circumferential membrane staining that is complete and >10% of tumor cells*</div><div><br/></div><div>Indeterminate:</div><div>Technical issues prevent the test from being reported as positive, negative, or equivocal.</div><div>Conditions may include:</div><div>Inadequate specimen handling</div><div>Artifacts (crush or edge artifacts) that make interpretation difficult</div><div>Analytic testing failure</div><div>Another specimen should be requested for testing to determine HER2 status.</div><div>Reason for indeterminate testing should be noted in a comment in the report.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ILC</title>
    <created>20180508T024914Z</created>
    <updated>20260302T083351Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Invasive lobular carcinoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows breast tissue infiltrated by neoplastic cells arranged in cords with Indian filing pattern. The tumor cells show mildly enlarged nuclei.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells show loss of E-cadherin, consistent with the diagnosis.</div><div>Histologic type: Invasive lobular carcinoma</div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>Grade II (score 6,7)</div><div>- Tubule formation: score 3</div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score 2</div><div>- Mitotic count: score 1</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div><div>4. Ki-67</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intraductal papillary with pseudoinvasion</title>
    <created>20170803T123645Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T080522Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Section shows papillary proliferation of ductal epithelial cells within dilated duct with preserved myoepithelial cells. There is entrapment of epithelial structures by fibrohyaline stroma, resulting in a pseudo invasive appearance. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the ductal epithelial cells are heterogeneously positive for CK5/6. P63 highlights the myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intraductal papilloma</title>
    <created>20160810T103117Z</created>
    <updated>20230626T071616Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Intraductal papilloma</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows papillary proliferation of ductal epithelial cells within dilated duct with preserved myoepithelial cells. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the ductal epithelial cells are heterogeneously positive for CK5/6. P63 highlights the myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intraductal papilloma with atypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH)</title>
    <created>20170217T025904Z</created>
    <updated>20250815T082513Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Intraductal papilloma with atypical ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows papillary proliferation of ductal epithelial cells within dilated duct with preserved surrounding myoepithelial cells. There is focal population of monotonous cells arranged in solid and cribriform patterns (_ mm in maximum dimension), suggestive of atypical ductal hyperplasia. </div><div><br/></div><div>Microcalcification is present inside the ADH and in benign mammary acini.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the proliferative ductal epithelial cells shows focal loss of CK5/6. P63 highlights the surrounding myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>The surgical margin is involved.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY (performed on section B): SMMHC, p63, CK5/6.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Invasive carcinoma with apocrine differentiation</title>
    <created>20250310T071725Z</created>
    <updated>20250310T072056Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Invasive carcinoma with apocrine differentiation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:
Section shows an infiltrating tumor comprised of large
epithelial cells with abundant eosinophilic and granular
cytoplasm, well defined cell borders, enlarged nuclei and
prominent nucleoli. The tumor cells are strongly positive
for AR, and negative for ER and PR, suggestive of apocrine
differentiation. A definite subtype can only be made on
the subsequent larger specimen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:
Histologic type: invasive carcinoma with apocrine
differentiation
Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):
Grade II (score 6,7)</div><ul><li><div>Tubule formation: score 3</div></li><li><div>Nuclear pleomorphism: score 2</div></li><li><div>Mitotic count: score 2</div></li></ul><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><ol><li><div>ER (Ab): Negative (0%)</div></li><li><div>PR (Ab): Negative (0%)</div></li><li><div>Her-2/neu (Ab): Equivocal (2+)</div></li><li><div>Ki-67: 40%</div></li><li><div>P63 immunostaining demonstrates the absence of myoepithelial cells at the periphery of invasive focus.</div></li><li><div>AR: Positive.</div></li></ol><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div><div><a href="evernote:///view/26224745/s227/5652d98a-75f1-48bf-8b49-b8f855595da5#7e617b9b-bedd-4e7d-b347-4add207cd883/9fa88e94-9907-434d-8e18-634482c75c16/">Invasive carcinoma with apocrine differentiation</a></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Invasive ductal carcinoma with mucin production.</title>
    <created>20200413T093319Z</created>
    <updated>20200413T093427Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Invasive ductal carcinoma with mucin production.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows nests of tumor cells invading the stroma and focally floating within lakes of extracellular mucin. The tumor cells exhibit marked cytologic atypia with eosinophilic cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>Grade </div><div>- Tubule formation: score    </div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score </div><div>- Mitotic count: score </div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive (_%, strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive (_%, strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): _</div><div>4. Ki-67: _%.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>LCIS [F] Atypia</title>
    <created>20140701T032038Z</created>
    <updated>20240823T044950Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source-url>https://tumourclassification.iarc.who.int/chaptercontent/32/13</source-url>
      <reminder-done-time>20170111T133200Z</reminder-done-time>
      <reminder-order>1470732369999</reminder-order>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);">lobular carcinoma in situ.</span></span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;">Sections show expanded acini featuring proliferation of discohesive cells with intracytoplasmic vacuoles (enlarged and mildly pleomorphic nuclei). Pagetoid spread of the terminal ducts is also seen. </span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;">NOTE: LCIS is a benign condition and is not treated as a carcinoma. It is properly considered a proliferative disease with associated risk for developing a breast cancer in the future and, therefore, is no longer included in the AJCC 8th ed. cancer staging system.</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>mammary hamartoma</title>
    <created>20190501T063740Z</created>
    <updated>20190501T063806Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>mammary hamartoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a circumscribed nodule composed of breast</div><div>ducts, lobules, fibrous stroma, and adipose tissue.</div><div>Microcalcifications are seen within the mammary acini.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Mastitis with abscess formation</title>
    <created>20170425T042255Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014954Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mastitis with abscess formation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows mammary tissue cores exhibiting a heavy infiltrate in fibroadipose tissue and in and around mammary lobules. The infiltrate is composed of acute and chronic inflammatory cells, and scattered histiocytes and some multinucleated giant cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>The GMS and PAS stains are negative for fungal organisms. Immunohistochemically, no invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by CK(AE1/AE3).</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>MCL with ADH</title>
    <created>20250304T060631Z</created>
    <updated>20250304T060809Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucocele-like lesion with atypical ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show round to ovoid cystically dilated spaces lined</div><div>by epithelial and myoepithelial cells in a sclerotic stroma.</div><div>The dilated ducts are focally filled by mucin with</div><div>extravasated mucin pools into surrounding stroma.</div><div>There is focal population of monotonous cells with Romen</div><div>bridge-like architecture (&lt;2 mm in maximum dimension),</div><div>suggestive of atypical ductal hyperplasia.</div><div>Microcalcifications are present inside the ADH and in benign</div><div>mammary acini.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the proliferative ductal epithelial</div><div>cells show loss of CK5/6.</div><div><br/></div><div>The margin is </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>metastatic carcinoma, consistent with mammary origin</title>
    <created>20190603T060548Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014821Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Metastatic carcinoma, consistent with mammary origin</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: arial;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Microscopic description:</span></span></div><div><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Section shows pulmonary tissue infiltrated by nests of neoplastic cells featuring vesicular nuclei with indistinct nucleoli. </span></span></div><div><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Immunohistochemically, these tumor cells are positive for GATA3 but not TTF1.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">The overall findings, taken together with clinical information, are compatible with metastatic invasive ductal carcinoma of mammary origin. </span></span></div><div><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);"> </span></span></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>metastatic IDC</title>
    <created>20230228T073743Z</created>
    <updated>20250923T043145Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Metastatic carcinoma, consistent with mammary origin.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show blood clots admixed with few cluster of tumor cells being positive for AE1/AE3 and GATA3.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>ER (Ab): Positive /Low Positive (1-10% of cells with nuclear positivity)/ Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+) /Equivocal (2+) /Negative (1+/0)</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>mucin-producing carcinoma.</title>
    <created>20181109T100036Z</created>
    <updated>20260408T041939Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucin-producing carcinoma. </div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows islands of tumor cells floating within lakes of extracellular mucin. The tumor cells exhibit mild cytologic atypia with relatively uniform nuclei and small amounts of eosinophilic cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>The overall features suggest a mucin-producing carcinoma, which can be either pure mucinous or mixed ductal-mucinous carcinoma. A definite diagnosis can only be made on the subsequent larger specimen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score):</div><div>Grade I (score 3-5)</div><div>- Tubule formation: score 2   </div><div>- Nuclear pleomorphism: score 1</div><div>- Mitotic count: score 1</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY:</div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive (_%, strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive (_%, strong)</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): _</div><div>4. Ki-67: _%.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.) </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Mucocele-like lesion [MCL]</title>
    <created>20170102T081805Z</created>
    <updated>20250304T060635Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucocele-like lesion.</div><div><br/></div><div>Sections show round to ovoid cystically dilated spaces lined by epithelial and myoepithelial cells in a sclerotic stroma. The dilated ducts are focally filled by mucin with extravasated mucin pools into surrounding stroma.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Mucocele-like lesion with focal atypical ductal hyperplasia</title>
    <created>20181102T012948Z</created>
    <updated>20181102T013020Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucocele-like lesion with focal atypical ductal hyperplasia</div><div><br/>
Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows round to ovoid cystically dilated spaces lined by epithelial and myoepithelial cells in a sclerotic stroma. The dilated ducts are focally filled by mucin with extravasated mucin pools into surrounding stroma. Microcalcifications are seen. There is focal proliferation of monotonous cells with bridging and second lumen formation, and with loss of CK5/6 in these proliferative cells, suggestive of atypical ductal hyperplasia.<br/></div><div>P63 and SMMHC highlight the preserved myoepithelial cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, the specimen shows a mucocele-like lesion with focal atypical ductal hyperplasia. Total excision of the mass is suggested because a more significant lesion cannot be comfortably excluded based on core biopsy sampling alone.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Normal mammary tissue BRE33</title>
    <created>20170719T050650Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014836Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div> Normal mammary tissue. See Note.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: This sample may not be representative of the lesion.  Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The core tissues include normal breast ducts and lobules, as well as fibrous and adipose stroma. No pathological changes, including microcalcifications or malignancy, are observed in these samples. Based on imaging findings, this sample may not be representative of the lesion.  Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the myoepithelial cells are highlighted by p63. No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Paget disease</title>
    <created>20190912T102555Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014927Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Paget disease.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows single cells or clusters of cells spread throughout the epidermis with epidermal ulceration.</div><div>The tumor cells have abundant pale cytoplasm, irregular large nucleus with prominent nucleoli.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for CK7 and EMA, and negative for p40, confirming the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>1. ER (Ab): negative (0%).</div><div>2. PR (Ab): negative (0%).</div><div>3. Her-2/neu (Ab): positive (3+).</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Papillary lesion</title>
    <created>20160810T103340Z</created>
    <updated>20231018T070318Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>papillary lesion.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows florid proliferation of ductal epithelial cells with preserved myoepithelial cells in focal papillary pattern.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the ductal epithelial cells are heterogeneously positive for CK5/6. P63 highlights the myoepithelial cells. Total excision is recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Papillary lesion (DD IPC, EPC)</title>
    <created>20170322T012255Z</created>
    <updated>20190917T074103Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows breast tissue with proliferative ductal cells with focal papillary pattern. The ductal cells show columnar shaped with enlarged and rounded nuclei and increased mitotic activity. Extracellular mucin is also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the proliferative ductal cells show loss of CK5/6 expression. P63 and SMMHC demonstrate the absence of myoepithelial cells in the fibrovascular cores.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a papillary lesion with differential diagnoses of intraductal papillary carcinoma or encapsulated papillary carcinoma. Total excision of the lesion is recommended for a definite diagnosis.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Papillary lesion with atypia</title>
    <created>20170720T132658Z</created>
    <updated>20170720T132929Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows florid proliferation of ductal epithelial cells with preserved surrounding myoepithelial cells in focal papillary pattern. Focal atypical ductal proliferation with monomorphic appearance is seen. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the ductal epithelial cells show focal loss of CK5/6. P63 highlights the myoepithelial cells at the periphery as well as within the fibrovascular cores, but lost in the atypical foci. Total excision is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Papillary lesion, needle biopsy (Attenuation of p63)</title>
    <created>20170124T010042Z</created>
    <updated>20230629T075457Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>The breast tissue strips are fragmented and reveal fibrotic areas and a florid proliferation of ductal epithelial cells that are immunoreactive to CK5/6 and form compact-arranged ductules or solid sheets, surrounded by myoepithelial cells as </div><div>highlighted by p63 immunostain. Attenuation of intermingling myoepithelial cells is demonstrated by p63 stain. Total excision of the lesion may be needed for an accurate diagnosis. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>PATHOLOGY REPORT — BREAST CORE BIOPSY</title>
    <created>20260401T085941Z</created>
    <updated>20260401T090125Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>PATHOLOGY REPORT — BREAST CORE BIOPSY</div><div>Clinical Diagnosis: L breast mass
Important History: L breast mass
Specimen: L breast mass core biopsy</div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION</div><div>Histologic type: Invasive carcinoma of no special type (ductal).</div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham histologic score): Grade II (score 7)
Tubule formation: score 3
Nuclear pleomorphism: score 3
Mitotic count: score 1</div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY</div><ol><li><div>ER (Ab): Negative</div></li><li><div>PR (Ab): Negative</div></li><li><div>Her-2/neu (Ab): Positive (3+)</div></li><li><div>Ki-67: 30%</div></li><li><div>P63 immunostaining (SMMHC) demonstrates the absence of myoepithelial cells at the periphery of invasive focus.</div></li></ol><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Perilobular hemangioma</title>
    <created>20200421T024353Z</created>
    <updated>20200421T024659Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>A perilobular hemangioma is seen, which is characterized by aggregate of capillary-sized blood vessels in association with a lobule. The endothelial cells are highlighted by CD31 but not S100 confirming the diagnosis.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20220415T053354Z</created>
    <updated>20220415T053926Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Phyllodes tumor, borderline.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic Type: Phyllodes tumor, borderline</div><div>Tumor Size: </div><div>Stromal Cellularity: Moderate</div><div>Stromal Atypia: Mild to moderate</div><div>Stromal Overgrowth: Absent</div><div>Mitotic Rate: 9 mitoses per 10 HPFs</div><div>Histologic Tumor Border: Focally permeative</div><div>Malignant Heterologous Elements: Not identified</div><div>Margin: Margin involved by phyllodes tumor</div><div>Regional Lymph Node Status: Not applicable.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Pseudoangiomatous stomal hyperplasia [PASH]</title>
    <created>20191121T064951Z</created>
    <updated>20230629T061143Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Pseudoangiomatous stomal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows proliferative stromal cells forming slit-like clefts, surrounding benign mammary ducts are seen.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, these spindle cells are positive for CD34 but not CD31, AE1/AE3 or p63.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: PASH can be associated with other benign or malignant lesions, or as the stromal component of fibroepithelial lesions.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Sclerosing adenosis (with IHC)</title>
    <created>20161110T145508Z</created>
    <updated>20241112T063404Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sclerosing adenosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show (a demarcated tumor composed of) angular or dilated tubules in a sclerotic stroma, (accompanied by focal proliferation of epithelial cells with second lumen formation). Microcalcifications are also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the proliferated epithelial cells focally express CK5/6, suggesting usual ductal hyperplasia. SMMHC demonstrates the surrounding myoepithelial cells. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>sclerosing lymphocytic mastitis (please see NOTE).</title>
    <created>20190121T042814Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T021104Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>sclerosing lymphocytic mastitis (please see NOTE).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The breast biopsy shows stromal fibrosis, periductal and</div><div>perivascular lymphocytic infiltrates, and epithelioid</div><div>myofibroblasts in the stroma.</div><div><br/></div><div>P63 highlights the preserved myoepithelial cells. No</div><div>invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3. CD3 and CD20</div><div>demonstrate the distribution of T and B lymphocytes.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: sclerosing lymphocytic mastitis is often associated</div><div>with diabetes (diabetic mastopathy). Clinical correlation is</div><div>recommanded.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Siliconoma</title>
    <created>20170509T051809Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T014922Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Siliconoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows benign mammary tissue and a lesion showing variable-sized spaces</div><div>surrounded by histiocytes and multinucleated giant cells.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>SIZE/Prior biopsy or excision</title>
    <created>20190610T075910Z</created>
    <updated>20190610T080335Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>file:///C:\Users\h3d0\Desktop\temp_LAVH.doc</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;新細明體&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;-en-paragraph:true;">NOTE: If there has been a prior core needle biopsy or incisional biopsy showing a larger area of invasion than in the excisional specimen, the largest dimension of the invasive carcinoma in the prior specimen should be used for T classification. Please correlate with previous pathological report.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>solid papillary carcinoma associated with microinvasive carcinoma (pT1mi) [microinvasion]</title>
    <created>20240703T031719Z</created>
    <updated>20240703T032008Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>solid papillary carcinoma associated with microinvasive carcinoma (pT1mi).</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION: </div><div>Histologic type: solid papillary carcinoma associated with </div><div>  microinvasive carcinoma </div><div>Histologic grade (Nottingham modification of the Bloom-Richardson grading system): I    </div><div>  Tubule formation: 2</div><div>  Nuclear pleomorphism: 2</div><div>  Mitotic count: 1</div><div>NOTE: microinvasion is not graded according to Cancer</div><div>  Protocol Templates of College of American Pathologists.</div><div>Maximum size of invasive cancer: two foci of microinvasion, </div><div>  up to 0.1 cm, measured on the histologic slide </div><div>  [pT1mi: &lt;=1 mm (microinvasion)]</div><div>Extent of tumor: </div><div>  Skin involvement: absent</div><div>Chest wall invasion deeper than pectoralis muscle: not applicable</div><div>Nipple: not assessed</div><div>Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS): solid papillary carcinoma</div><div>Extensive intraductal carcinoma status (DCIS>25%): positive</div><div>Peritumoral lymphovascular invasion: absent</div><div>Perineural invasion: absent</div><div>Microcalcification: present inside solid papillary carcinoma in situ</div><div>Surgical margin:</div><div>  Deep:  cm; </div><div>  3 o'clock direction:  cm;  </div><div>  6 o'clock direction:  cm;  </div><div>  9 o'clock direction:  cm;  </div><div>  12 o'clock direction:  cm;  </div><div>  Anterior (superficial):  cm. </div><div>Lymph nodes (Positive/Total): not assessed</div><div>Treatment Effect: not applicable</div><div>Immunohistochemical study:  </div><div>  SMMHC and P63: Absence of myoepithelial rimming </div><div>  Estrogen receptor): Positive (99%, strongly) </div><div>  Progesterone receptor): Positive (2%, strongly) </div><div>  HER-2/neu protein: Negative (score: 1+)</div><div>  Ki-67: 10% nuclear staining </div><div>  Synaptophysin: focally positive</div><div>pTNM: pT1mi(m) (AJCC cancer staging system, 8th edition)</div><div>TNM descriptors: m(multiple).</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Spindle cell lesion</title>
    <created>20170308T010459Z</created>
    <updated>20250603T015005Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows mammary tissue cores composed of mammary ducts featuring usual ductal hyperplasia in a background of bland-looking spindle cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, myoepithelial cells surrounding the ducts are highlighted by p63. The spindle cells are negative for 34betaE12 and P63. The spindle cells are stained blue by Masson trichrome stain.</div><div><br/></div><div>The differential diagnoses include fibroepithelial lesion or other mesenchymal tumors,  of either benign or low malignant potential. Total excision of the lesion is recommended for a definite diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Spindle cell neoplasm Bx (Borderline or Malignant phyllodes)</title>
    <created>20230911T030013Z</created>
    <updated>20230911T030033Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Spindle cell neoplasm. See description.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows breast tissue with a lesion composed of</div><div>spindle cells bearing moderate cellular atypia with</div><div>increased cellularity. Occasional mitosis is seen. Focally</div><div>dilated ductal epithelium is seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the spindle cells are diffusely</div><div>positive for bcl-2 and SMA but not AE1/AE3 and p63. CD34 is</div><div>focally positive.</div><div><br/></div><div>The categorization of this spindle cell lesion is difficult</div><div>in this small biopsied smample. Based on histology and</div><div>immunoprofile, the differential diagnosis includes phyllodes</div><div>tumor of either borderline or malignant. Metaplastic</div><div>carcinoma is less likely due to complete absence of AE1/AE3</div><div>and p63 stainings. A soft tissue neoplasm is less likely but</div><div>cannot be completely excluded.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Suggestive of fibroepithelial lesion</title>
    <created>20180306T091555Z</created>
    <updated>20260422T081824Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: 'Microsoft YaHei';">Benign mammary tissue (please </span>see NOTE).</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: 'Microsoft YaHei';">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: 'Microsoft YaHei';">The tissue cores are composed predominantly of normal breast </span>tissue with fibrocystic change. There are tissue fragments showing mild proliferation of mammary glands set in a fibrous stroma. </div><div><br/></div><div>By immunohistochemistry, p63 immunostain demonstrates the preserved myoepithelial cells. </div><div><br/></div><div>No malignancy is seen in this specimen.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: 'Microsoft YaHei';">NOTE: Based on the imaging finding, this specimen could </span>either be suggestive of a fibroepithelial lesion or be not representative for the lesion. </div><div>Re-biopsy is suggested if malignancy is suspected clinically.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Tubular adenoma</title>
    <created>20180206T064610Z</created>
    <updated>20230713T062604Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Tubular adenoma</div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;"><br/></span></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows small </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">round tubular structures lined by regular epithelial and </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">myoepithelial cells surrounded by scant loosely cellular </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">stroma.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Tubular carcinoma.</title>
    <created>20200312T235352Z</created>
    <updated>20200312T235818Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>More than 90% of the tumors are composed of tubules and</div><div>glands with open lumina lined by a single layer or</div><div>neoplastic epithelium, which is consistent with the</div><div>diagnosis of tubular carcinoma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>UDH</title>
    <created>20161101T235645Z</created>
    <updated>20240520T054252Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>usual ductal hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Sections show breast tissue revealing proliferation of epithelial cells lined by myoepithelial cells with microcalcifications in the lumen. Fibrosis is seen within the stroma.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the myoepithelial cells are highlighted by SMMHC and p63. Staining for CK5/6 is heterogeneously positive in the proliferative epithelial cells. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>因應評鑑需求 需修改之部位與原申請單內容不同需填寫紙本申請書</title>
    <created>20250909T035725Z</created>
    <updated>20260519T034912Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>因應評鑑需求 需修改之部位與原申請單內容不同需填寫紙本申請書</div><div>如需申請單填寫協助 請洽病理科前台書記（分機 3401／3406） 謝謝!</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>莊茂德margin</title>
    <created>20220425T032921Z</created>
    <updated>20220425T033139Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>However, because the specimen is not oriented, this involved margin may represent margin transected from partial mastectomy specimen. The exact margin status</div><div>cannot be evaluated. Clinical correlation is recommended.</div><div>      (This case was discussed with Dr Chuang on 2022/04/25 10 am)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>請確定microcalcifications有沒有切乾淨</title>
    <created>20190730T075951Z</created>
    <updated>20190730T080256Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Only few microcalcifications in the mammary acini are present. Clinico-radiological correlation to determine whether all calcifications have been removed is suggested.</div><div>No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
